WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.992 align:middle line:90%


00:00:00.992 --> 00:00:04.464 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:04.464 --> 00:00:28.300 align:middle line:90%


00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:31.330 align:middle line:84%
>> We have a very skewed
sense of our relationship with

00:00:31.330 --> 00:00:34.433 align:middle line:84%
microorganisms in general
and bacteria specifically.

00:00:34.433 --> 00:00:37.610 align:middle line:90%


00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:40.870 align:middle line:84%
>> They collectively outweigh
human beings by 100 million

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:41.670 align:middle line:90%
times.

00:00:41.670 --> 00:00:44.200 align:middle line:90%


00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:48.040 align:middle line:84%
They can replicate 500,000
times faster than we can.

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:51.210 align:middle line:90%


00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:53.180 align:middle line:84%
And they've been doing
this for 1,000 times

00:00:53.180 --> 00:00:54.870 align:middle line:84%
longer than our
species has existed.

00:00:54.870 --> 00:00:59.320 align:middle line:90%


00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:04.900 align:middle line:84%
>> We've just touched the corner
of understanding the diversity

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:07.870 align:middle line:84%
of the microbes
that are out there.

00:01:07.870 --> 00:01:09.330 align:middle line:84%
We've barely
scratched the surface.

00:01:09.330 --> 00:01:12.480 align:middle line:90%


00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:17.160 align:middle line:84%
And we need to understand
this because, again, they

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:19.818 align:middle line:90%
make plants functional.

00:01:19.818 --> 00:01:22.510 align:middle line:90%


00:01:22.510 --> 00:01:26.020 align:middle line:84%
They affect the movement
of methane, and hydrogen,

00:01:26.020 --> 00:01:30.340 align:middle line:90%
and nitrogen, and phosphorus.

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:36.850 align:middle line:84%
They affect the carbon fixation
and the plankton in the oceans.

00:01:36.850 --> 00:01:38.980 align:middle line:84%
Viewing them as
important players

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:41.440 align:middle line:84%
in our ecosystem in
the same way people

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:45.400 align:middle line:84%
have viewed forests and
grasslands would probably

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:47.230 align:middle line:84%
make us treat the
world in a better way.

00:01:47.230 --> 00:02:05.086 align:middle line:90%


00:02:05.086 --> 00:02:08.558 align:middle line:90%
[CHATTER]

00:02:08.558 --> 00:02:20.960 align:middle line:90%


00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:22.240 align:middle line:90%
>> My name is Robert Beam.

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:23.883 align:middle line:90%
I'm Jesse's father.

00:02:23.883 --> 00:02:27.337 align:middle line:90%
[CHATTER]

00:02:27.337 --> 00:02:28.170 align:middle line:90%
>> I'm Christy Beam.

00:02:28.170 --> 00:02:29.280 align:middle line:90%
I'm Jesse's stepmom.

00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:32.605 align:middle line:90%
[CHATTER]

00:02:32.605 --> 00:02:34.505 align:middle line:90%


00:02:34.505 --> 00:02:36.880 align:middle line:84%
>> And then just step
out for a second.

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:38.320 align:middle line:90%
And we'll pull this up.

00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:40.360 align:middle line:84%
>> We were actually
at cross country camp.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:41.560 align:middle line:90%
>> See how tall you are.

00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:43.101 align:middle line:84%
>> And I think it
was the second day,

00:02:43.101 --> 00:02:44.391 align:middle line:90%
he started developing a fever.

00:02:44.391 --> 00:02:46.390 align:middle line:84%
The following day we came
back here to Kentucky.

00:02:46.390 --> 00:02:47.431 align:middle line:90%
>> Now you can step away.

00:02:47.431 --> 00:02:49.390 align:middle line:90%
>> And he was really--

00:02:49.390 --> 00:02:50.500 align:middle line:90%
getting dramatic with him.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.700 align:middle line:84%
Jesse Beam does not
do sick very well.

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:53.930 align:middle line:90%
So he was kind of--

00:02:53.930 --> 00:02:55.290 align:middle line:90%
I thought he was playing it.

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:57.040 align:middle line:84%
And he was kind of
moping around the house

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:00.330 align:middle line:84%
and crawling at one
point out of his bedroom.

00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:01.570 align:middle line:90%
And I told him to get up.

00:03:01.570 --> 00:03:02.370 align:middle line:90%
And he did.

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:05.266 align:middle line:90%
So you think he's playing it.

00:03:05.266 --> 00:03:06.640 align:middle line:84%
Next day while
I'm at the office,

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:09.115 align:middle line:84%
he calls me wanting
to go to the hospital.

00:03:09.115 --> 00:03:10.240 align:middle line:90%
So I call his pediatrician.

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:12.684 align:middle line:84%
And she said, get him
in here right now.

00:03:12.684 --> 00:03:13.600 align:middle line:90%
Finally got us a room.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:15.010 align:middle line:90%
Got an X-ray.

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:18.579 align:middle line:84%
They found pneumonia
in his right lung.

00:03:18.579 --> 00:03:20.370 align:middle line:84%
Figured that was what
we were dealing with.

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:22.661 align:middle line:84%
So I called Christy and told
her we're in the hospital.

00:03:22.661 --> 00:03:23.852 align:middle line:90%
He's got pneumonia.

00:03:23.852 --> 00:03:25.060 align:middle line:90%
She's trying to calm me down.

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:26.310 align:middle line:90%
Told me not to worry about it.

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:27.680 align:middle line:90%
You know, kids get pneumonia.

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:28.600 align:middle line:90%
They'll be fine.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:31.630 align:middle line:84%
He'll probably stay in the
hospital for a day or two.

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:33.970 align:middle line:84%
All night long he just kept
getting worse and worse.

00:03:33.970 --> 00:03:36.210 align:middle line:84%
His temperature would
get pretty high.

00:03:36.210 --> 00:03:38.470 align:middle line:84%
Or, at least his body
temperature was high.

00:03:38.470 --> 00:03:41.200 align:middle line:84%
But his oral temperature was
never really spiking real high.

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:43.720 align:middle line:90%


00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:47.150 align:middle line:84%
He started hallucinating around
4:00, 5:00 in the morning.

00:03:47.150 --> 00:03:47.950 align:middle line:90%
And that's when I--

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:49.533 align:middle line:84%
I went to help him
go to the bathroom.

00:03:49.533 --> 00:03:52.480 align:middle line:84%
And when we stood him up,
his front was really clammy.

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:54.460 align:middle line:84%
And his back would
almost burn your hands.

00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:56.520 align:middle line:90%
And I told the nurse that.

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:57.320 align:middle line:90%
So she came in.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:59.580 align:middle line:84%
And they had to do a
rectal temperature.

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:04.030 align:middle line:84%
And his internal temperature
at that point was 105.9.

00:04:04.030 --> 00:04:05.710 align:middle line:84%
She called in the
critical care team.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.440 align:middle line:84%
His pediatrician showed up, who
made the call that he needed

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:11.290 align:middle line:90%
to be at a pediatric hospital.

00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:13.535 align:middle line:84%
Again, I'm still
thinking pneumonia.

00:04:13.535 --> 00:04:15.410 align:middle line:84%
So I told Jesse I was
going run to the house,

00:04:15.410 --> 00:04:17.649 align:middle line:84%
get him some clean
clothes, get him his games.

00:04:17.649 --> 00:04:20.149 align:middle line:84%
And I'd be down
there to Vanderbilt.

00:04:20.149 --> 00:04:22.237 align:middle line:84%
In about-- I don't know
how much longer it was.

00:04:22.237 --> 00:04:24.820 align:middle line:84%
But I was about Goodlettsville
when they called me and told me

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:25.695 align:middle line:90%
that they were there.

00:04:25.695 --> 00:04:27.170 align:middle line:90%
They'd made it.

00:04:27.170 --> 00:04:28.640 align:middle line:90%
Jesse made the flight well.

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:30.400 align:middle line:84%
But his body was
doing a lot of work.

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:41.854 align:middle line:90%


00:04:41.854 --> 00:04:45.340 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:46.260 align:middle line:90%


00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:48.260 align:middle line:84%
That's when they told me
they put him in a coma.

00:04:48.260 --> 00:04:51.746 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:04:51.746 --> 00:04:53.240 align:middle line:90%


00:04:53.240 --> 00:04:56.726 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:04:56.726 --> 00:05:00.212 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:05:00.212 --> 00:05:04.085 align:middle line:90%


00:05:04.085 --> 00:05:05.210 align:middle line:90%
We started with daptomycin.

00:05:05.210 --> 00:05:06.590 align:middle line:90%
And then we went to clindamycin.

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:10.250 align:middle line:84%
We went to vancomycin, which
he finished off vanc upstairs.

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:14.210 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, and he was on
all three at one time.

00:05:14.210 --> 00:05:17.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's whenever
they told us that, look,

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:18.440 align:middle line:90%
he's on all three medicines.

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:21.270 align:middle line:90%
We've done everything we can do.

00:05:21.270 --> 00:05:22.070 align:middle line:90%
You know--

00:05:22.070 --> 00:05:23.903 align:middle line:84%
>> If the bacteria
doesn't stop growing now,

00:05:23.903 --> 00:05:25.664 align:middle line:90%
then there's nothing else.

00:05:25.664 --> 00:05:27.080 align:middle line:84%
>> There's nothing
else we can do.

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:28.775 align:middle line:84%
We've got nothing
else to pull from.

00:05:28.775 --> 00:05:32.240 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:05:32.240 --> 00:05:35.705 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:05:35.705 --> 00:05:46.120 align:middle line:90%


00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:50.710 align:middle line:84%
>> Antibiotics are basically
poisons that kill bacteria

00:05:50.710 --> 00:05:51.820 align:middle line:90%
and don't kill us.

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:57.790 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:00.470 align:middle line:84%
They often have some effects
on the human body as well.

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:02.740 align:middle line:84%
But for infections, it's
going to do one of two things

00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:03.730 align:middle line:90%
to a bacteria.

00:06:03.730 --> 00:06:05.530 align:middle line:84%
It either kills it or
it makes it stronger.

00:06:05.530 --> 00:06:08.932 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:08.932 --> 00:06:11.860 align:middle line:90%


00:06:11.860 --> 00:06:13.950 align:middle line:84%
>> But what we do
with antibiotics--

00:06:13.950 --> 00:06:18.480 align:middle line:84%
because we give the wrong
doses of antibiotics to people,

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:21.240 align:middle line:84%
or we give the right doses, but
people end up dosing themselves

00:06:21.240 --> 00:06:24.180 align:middle line:84%
incorrectly because they don't
take a full prescription,

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:27.810 align:middle line:84%
or because we give antibiotics
to healthy farm animals,

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:29.760 align:middle line:84%
what we do in all
those situations

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:32.820 align:middle line:84%
is we set up a sort of
Darwinian battleground

00:06:32.820 --> 00:06:36.420 align:middle line:84%
within the body of the
human or the animal who's

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:40.200 align:middle line:84%
getting the antibiotics, in
which the weak susceptible

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:42.580 align:middle line:84%
bacteria are knocked
out by the drug.

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:43.980 align:middle line:90%
But the strong survive.

00:06:43.980 --> 00:06:46.900 align:middle line:10%
>> And it unfortunately occurs
more rapidly than you might

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:47.700 align:middle line:10%
think.

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:49.040 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:52.429 align:middle line:10%
Because they go so quickly
as a community of organisms,

00:06:52.429 --> 00:06:54.720 align:middle line:10%
if there's a way to become
resistant, they can find it.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:58.136 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:58.136 --> 00:07:02.540 align:middle line:90%


00:07:02.540 --> 00:07:04.940 align:middle line:10%
>> About three quarters of
the way through my fellowship,

00:07:04.940 --> 00:07:07.740 align:middle line:10%
we began to see just an
explosion of highly resistant

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:08.540 align:middle line:10%
infections.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:11.420 align:middle line:10%
And that was concordant
with it happening all

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:12.930 align:middle line:10%
over the country and the world.

00:07:12.930 --> 00:07:15.330 align:middle line:10%
There's nothing unique
about our setting.

00:07:15.330 --> 00:07:17.120 align:middle line:10%
And I remember the
first patient that I

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:20.270 align:middle line:10%
took care of who had an
untreatable infection.

00:07:20.270 --> 00:07:21.600 align:middle line:10%
Could not be treated.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:27.020 align:middle line:84%
And it was a woman in her 20s,
who had two small kids, who

00:07:27.020 --> 00:07:27.950 align:middle line:90%
had leukemia.

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:33.788 align:middle line:90%


00:07:33.788 --> 00:07:36.972 align:middle line:90%
[CLEARS THROAT]

00:07:36.972 --> 00:07:37.772 align:middle line:90%


00:07:37.772 --> 00:07:40.262 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:07:40.262 --> 00:07:43.748 align:middle line:90%
[COUGHS]

00:07:43.748 --> 00:07:46.238 align:middle line:90%


00:07:46.238 --> 00:07:49.724 align:middle line:90%
[CLEARS THROAT]

00:07:49.724 --> 00:07:53.220 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:55.230 align:middle line:84%
And she developed an
infection in her blood

00:07:55.230 --> 00:07:56.490 align:middle line:90%
by an acinetobacter.

00:07:56.490 --> 00:07:59.070 align:middle line:90%


00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:00.750 align:middle line:84%
So we started treating
it with the drug

00:08:00.750 --> 00:08:02.460 align:middle line:84%
that we had left
at the time, which

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:05.280 align:middle line:90%
was a drug called imipenem.

00:08:05.280 --> 00:08:06.690 align:middle line:90%
That was the big gun.

00:08:06.690 --> 00:08:08.700 align:middle line:90%
That was the last ditch.

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:13.030 align:middle line:84%
And she looked like she was
getting better at first.

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:15.570 align:middle line:84%
But then the
infection came back.

00:08:15.570 --> 00:08:18.380 align:middle line:84%
And it was resistant
to the imipenem.

00:08:18.380 --> 00:08:22.530 align:middle line:84%
It developed resistance in the
middle of a course of therapy.

00:08:22.530 --> 00:08:28.260 align:middle line:84%
And when it came back, I have
this just vivid recollection

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:30.110 align:middle line:84%
of looking at the
computer screen.

00:08:30.110 --> 00:08:32.190 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:32.190 --> 00:08:34.950 align:middle line:84%
And you just see a printout
on the computer screen

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:38.909 align:middle line:84%
of all the antibiotics that
the bacteria is resistant to--

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:41.809 align:middle line:84%
resistant, resistant,
resistant, resistant, resistant.

00:08:41.809 --> 00:08:42.780 align:middle line:90%
There was nothing.

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:45.040 align:middle line:90%
It was resistant to everything.

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:49.860 align:middle line:84%
And I couldn't fathom
how in the 21st century

00:08:49.860 --> 00:08:53.370 align:middle line:84%
an infectious disease specialist
would run out of stuff.

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:54.750 align:middle line:90%
I mean this is--

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:57.900 align:middle line:84%
since penicillin, we've
expected that we're

00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:02.040 align:middle line:84%
going to have relatively
inexpensive, safe, tremendously

00:09:02.040 --> 00:09:05.440 align:middle line:84%
effective drugs to
treat infections.

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:09.040 align:middle line:84%
And this woman had
returned to 1935.

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:12.120 align:middle line:84%
She had returned to
the pre-antibiotic era.

00:09:12.120 --> 00:09:13.230 align:middle line:90%
And she died.

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:15.171 align:middle line:90%


00:09:15.171 --> 00:09:16.170 align:middle line:90%
There was nothing to do.

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:23.960 align:middle line:90%


00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:28.400 align:middle line:84%
>> Antibiotics were the only
thing we ever had in all

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:33.760 align:middle line:84%
of human history that really
stopped infectious diseases.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:39.430 align:middle line:10%
And we took that just
miraculous, precious substance,

00:09:39.430 --> 00:09:41.230 align:middle line:10%
and we completely squandered it.

00:09:41.230 --> 00:09:46.090 align:middle line:84%
And it astonishes me sometimes
that we don't ask ourselves,

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:48.650 align:middle line:84%
how is it that we
squandered this?

00:09:48.650 --> 00:09:50.250 align:middle line:90%
And why can't we stop?

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:59.731 align:middle line:90%


00:09:59.731 --> 00:10:03.224 align:middle line:90%
[WAVES CRASHING]

00:10:03.224 --> 00:10:04.222 align:middle line:90%


00:10:04.222 --> 00:10:07.715 align:middle line:90%
[CHEERING]

00:10:07.715 --> 00:10:11.208 align:middle line:90%
[WAVES CRASHING]

00:10:11.208 --> 00:10:19.240 align:middle line:90%


00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:21.710 align:middle line:84%
>> I came home from
work one afternoon.

00:10:21.710 --> 00:10:24.020 align:middle line:84%
I'd been working under
a boat all day painting.

00:10:24.020 --> 00:10:26.280 align:middle line:90%
And I was extra stiff.

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:27.080 align:middle line:90%
My back hurt.

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:29.850 align:middle line:84%
So I thought, well, maybe
I'll get in the bathtub.

00:10:29.850 --> 00:10:31.270 align:middle line:90%
We have a Jacuzzi tub.

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:35.130 align:middle line:84%
So I filled it up with
hot water and got in it.

00:10:35.130 --> 00:10:41.900 align:middle line:84%
And that's pretty much
the last thing I remember.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:42.740 align:middle line:90%
>> But I remember.

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:44.195 align:middle line:90%
>> Glad she remembers.

00:10:44.195 --> 00:10:48.350 align:middle line:10%
>> We also thought that we
might be sore because we were

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:51.980 align:middle line:10%
training really hard for the
