00:22:52.256 --> 00:22:53.380 align:middle line:90%
isn't going to ruin things.

00:22:53.380 --> 00:22:55.120 align:middle line:84%
And what if I'm wrong
about this patient?

00:22:55.120 --> 00:22:58.934 align:middle line:84%
It could really hurt her
or him if it's not a virus.

00:22:58.934 --> 00:23:00.100 align:middle line:90%
And I don't give an antibi--

00:23:00.100 --> 00:23:02.260 align:middle line:84%
I'm just going to
give the script

00:23:02.260 --> 00:23:04.570 align:middle line:84%
and give them the
antibiotic just to be sure.

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:07.120 align:middle line:84%
If you don't address
that fear that

00:23:07.120 --> 00:23:10.540 align:middle line:84%
occurs at that moment when
that patient is the physician's

00:23:10.540 --> 00:23:13.514 align:middle line:84%
responsibility, not
society at large,

00:23:13.514 --> 00:23:14.680 align:middle line:90%
then it's not going to work.

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:17.146 align:middle line:90%


00:23:17.146 --> 00:23:19.520 align:middle line:10%
>> Where that gets really
challenging for us as providers

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:23.390 align:middle line:10%
is that when we see patients
who have cough, and fever,

00:23:23.390 --> 00:23:26.300 align:middle line:10%
and are missing school
or missing work,

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:30.500 align:middle line:10%
we feel a need to be able to
intervene to be able to cut

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:33.792 align:middle line:10%
those symptoms short and
get people back to health.

00:23:33.792 --> 00:23:35.750 align:middle line:84%
Since we don't have good
therapies for viruses,

00:23:35.750 --> 00:23:38.750 align:middle line:84%
we tend to focus a lot on
those bacterial infections

00:23:38.750 --> 00:23:40.790 align:middle line:90%
that we do have antibiotics for.

00:23:40.790 --> 00:23:43.610 align:middle line:84%
The problem is is that for
every patient that we treat

00:23:43.610 --> 00:23:47.450 align:middle line:84%
with antibiotics we're breeding
a certain sense of resistance

00:23:47.450 --> 00:23:51.050 align:middle line:84%
in the community, that's fine
for infections that absolutely

00:23:51.050 --> 00:23:52.640 align:middle line:90%
require antibiotics.

00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:54.470 align:middle line:84%
But where we really
get into trouble

00:23:54.470 --> 00:23:57.920 align:middle line:84%
is that we prescribe antibiotics
for maybe five people.

00:23:57.920 --> 00:24:00.929 align:middle line:84%
Maybe only two or three of
them actually need antibiotics.

00:24:00.929 --> 00:24:03.470 align:middle line:84%
And only two or three of them
will those antibiotics actually

00:24:03.470 --> 00:24:04.640 align:middle line:90%
make them better faster.

00:24:04.640 --> 00:24:07.580 align:middle line:84%
>> And we need things like
rapid diagnostic tests.

00:24:07.580 --> 00:24:11.210 align:middle line:84%
So when this patient is
in my office, I run a test

00:24:11.210 --> 00:24:12.350 align:middle line:90%
and a printout comes out.

00:24:12.350 --> 00:24:14.570 align:middle line:84%
And it says, oh, this
patient has a virus.

00:24:14.570 --> 00:24:16.730 align:middle line:90%
Now I have no more fear.

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:19.170 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm comfortable
explaining to the patient

00:24:19.170 --> 00:24:19.970 align:middle line:90%
you have a virus.

00:24:19.970 --> 00:24:21.210 align:middle line:84%
We don't have any
treatment for it.

00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:22.501 align:middle line:90%
But it's just going to go away.

00:24:22.501 --> 00:24:25.710 align:middle line:90%
You don't need an antibiotic.

00:24:25.710 --> 00:24:32.360 align:middle line:84%
>> If you have a cold,
stay home, stay in bed.

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:34.820 align:middle line:84%
This is the prescription
which common sense

00:24:34.820 --> 00:24:39.220 align:middle line:90%
and medical science recommend.

00:24:39.220 --> 00:24:41.090 align:middle line:84%
>> And that feeling
of being ineffective,

00:24:41.090 --> 00:24:46.100 align:middle line:84%
that feeling of not being able
to cure all ills is sometimes

00:24:46.100 --> 00:24:47.620 align:middle line:90%
really tough.

00:24:47.620 --> 00:24:49.760 align:middle line:84%
I've taken care of
several teenagers

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:51.980 align:middle line:84%
over the past few years
that have suffered

00:24:51.980 --> 00:24:54.460 align:middle line:84%
from community acquired
methicillin-resistant staph

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:55.850 align:middle line:90%
aureus infections.

00:24:55.850 --> 00:24:57.620 align:middle line:84%
In all of those
situations, I remember

00:24:57.620 --> 00:25:01.700 align:middle line:84%
at least one moment where I
had to tell the family that I

00:25:01.700 --> 00:25:03.980 align:middle line:84%
didn't think their child
was going to survive

00:25:03.980 --> 00:25:06.140 align:middle line:90%
this devastating infection.

00:25:06.140 --> 00:25:08.390 align:middle line:84%
And that's typically done
in an environment where

00:25:08.390 --> 00:25:10.340 align:middle line:90%
the child's on a ventilator.

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:13.580 align:middle line:84%
They may be on a cardiac bypass
unit called ECMO, where we're

00:25:13.580 --> 00:25:17.450 align:middle line:84%
doing all of the work for them,
doing the work of the kidneys,

00:25:17.450 --> 00:25:19.370 align:middle line:90%
and the heart, and the lungs.

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:21.530 align:middle line:84%
It's usually after
a very grueling week

00:25:21.530 --> 00:25:25.880 align:middle line:84%
or maybe two weeks of antibiotic
use that is not effective.

00:25:25.880 --> 00:25:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And it's usually in
the setting where

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:29.090 align:middle line:84%
I have the
conversation that we've

00:25:29.090 --> 00:25:32.960 align:middle line:84%
been able to have some
victory over the bacteria.

00:25:32.960 --> 00:25:35.450 align:middle line:84%
But because the bacteria
was there for so long

00:25:35.450 --> 00:25:37.700 align:middle line:84%
and because the
inflammatory response

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:41.591 align:middle line:84%
was so great, that things aren't
going the way they need to be.

00:25:41.591 --> 00:25:42.391 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:25:42.391 --> 00:25:45.828 align:middle line:90%
[HAMMERING]

00:25:45.828 --> 00:25:50.738 align:middle line:90%


00:25:50.738 --> 00:25:54.175 align:middle line:90%
[HAMMERING]

00:25:54.175 --> 00:25:56.150 align:middle line:90%


00:25:56.150 --> 00:25:58.710 align:middle line:84%
>> It was within a day that they
had come back and told us it

00:25:58.710 --> 00:26:00.240 align:middle line:90%
was MRSA blood infection.

00:26:00.240 --> 00:26:04.088 align:middle line:90%


00:26:04.088 --> 00:26:06.246 align:middle line:84%
>> They think it
was in his nose.

00:26:06.246 --> 00:26:07.620 align:middle line:84%
And that it just
started floating

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.200 align:middle line:84%
through his bloodstream and
found a weak spot to attack,

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:12.030 align:middle line:90%
which ended up being his knee.

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:13.842 align:middle line:90%
Then it attacked his lungs.

00:26:13.842 --> 00:26:15.300 align:middle line:84%
And then it just
eventually started

00:26:15.300 --> 00:26:17.338 align:middle line:90%
taking all of his organs.

00:26:17.338 --> 00:26:20.302 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:26:20.302 --> 00:26:22.600 align:middle line:84%
He'll probably need
other surgeries.

00:26:22.600 --> 00:26:24.908 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:26:24.908 --> 00:26:30.124 align:middle line:84%
>> And the growth plate on his
thigh bone and his femur is

00:26:30.124 --> 00:26:31.250 align:middle line:90%
involved in all this.

00:26:31.250 --> 00:26:32.470 align:middle line:90%
So it's not growing.

00:26:32.470 --> 00:26:34.275 align:middle line:84%
So this leg is
shorter than this leg.

00:26:34.275 --> 00:26:39.241 align:middle line:84%
So probably down the
road we'll do something

00:26:39.241 --> 00:26:40.732 align:middle line:90%
to equal the two out.

00:26:40.732 --> 00:26:42.223 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:26:42.223 --> 00:26:43.217 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:26:43.217 --> 00:26:45.205 align:middle line:90%
>> Want me to get a couple more.

00:26:45.205 --> 00:26:46.696 align:middle line:84%
>> I think this
will do it, Susan.

00:26:46.696 --> 00:26:47.496 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:26:47.496 --> 00:26:50.369 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:26:50.369 --> 00:26:51.169 align:middle line:90%


00:26:51.169 --> 00:26:53.656 align:middle line:84%
>> Could you put family
in a room, please?

00:26:53.656 --> 00:26:55.520 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:26:55.520 --> 00:27:04.640 align:middle line:90%


00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:08.330 align:middle line:84%
>> The hardest part I think
was walking in there that first

00:27:08.330 --> 00:27:12.810 align:middle line:84%
time and seeing your child
laying there with medicine all

00:27:12.810 --> 00:27:13.610 align:middle line:90%
behind him--

00:27:13.610 --> 00:27:13.970 align:middle line:90%
>> Oh, Lord.

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:16.700 align:middle line:84%
>> --and wires, and machines,
and only enough room for you

00:27:16.700 --> 00:27:18.410 align:middle line:90%
to walk by his feet.

00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:20.300 align:middle line:90%
And you can't do anything.

00:27:20.300 --> 00:27:22.745 align:middle line:90%
And we just felt helpless.

00:27:22.745 --> 00:27:31.915 align:middle line:90%


00:27:31.915 --> 00:27:33.890 align:middle line:90%
>> I don't know.

00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:40.414 align:middle line:84%
Because I mean nobody
wants to think about death.

00:27:40.414 --> 00:27:41.330 align:middle line:90%
You don't want to die.

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:49.730 align:middle line:90%


00:27:49.730 --> 00:27:51.990 align:middle line:84%
I just knew like it was
getting to the point--

00:27:51.990 --> 00:27:54.650 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I knew it
had to be serious.

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:57.600 align:middle line:84%
They wouldn't just fly me
down there for no reason.

00:27:57.600 --> 00:28:01.140 align:middle line:90%
And I just--

00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:02.145 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:28:02.145 --> 00:28:03.430 align:middle line:90%
I kind of gave up, I guess.

00:28:03.430 --> 00:28:06.280 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:28:06.280 --> 00:28:07.230 align:middle line:90%
>> 20 more.

00:28:07.230 --> 00:28:11.030 align:middle line:90%
[CHATTER]

00:28:11.030 --> 00:28:15.180 align:middle line:84%
>> Like the stuff I still take
for granted I'd say is school.

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:19.180 align:middle line:84%
But things I don't take
for granted that I used to

00:28:19.180 --> 00:28:21.090 align:middle line:90%
is like--

00:28:21.090 --> 00:28:23.910 align:middle line:84%
before all this happened,
like taking a shower.

00:28:23.910 --> 00:28:27.670 align:middle line:90%


00:28:27.670 --> 00:28:30.247 align:middle line:84%
The first time I got back in
the shower I was in hospital.

00:28:30.247 --> 00:28:31.330 align:middle line:90%
And my dad was helping me.

00:28:31.330 --> 00:28:33.246 align:middle line:84%
And I cried because that
was first time I felt

00:28:33.246 --> 00:28:34.490 align:middle line:90%
the water hit me on the feet.

00:28:34.490 --> 00:28:37.913 align:middle line:90%
[CHATTER]

00:28:37.913 --> 00:28:42.610 align:middle line:90%


00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:46.780 align:middle line:84%
>> This has affected
his life and long term.

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:48.190 align:middle line:90%
He keeps thinking.

00:28:48.190 --> 00:28:51.010 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to be better in a
month, or two months, or three

00:28:51.010 --> 00:28:51.810 align:middle line:90%
months.

00:28:51.810 --> 00:28:55.390 align:middle line:84%
And it's hard for him to try to
wrap his brain around the fact

00:28:55.390 --> 00:29:01.990 align:middle line:84%
that he's got plates, and
screws, and pins in his leg.

00:29:01.990 --> 00:29:03.520 align:middle line:90%
And his lung is--

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:04.470 align:middle line:90%
>> [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:04.470 --> 00:29:06.882 align:middle line:90%
>> --shrunken

00:29:06.882 --> 00:29:07.780 align:middle line:90%
>> Does that hurt?

00:29:07.780 --> 00:29:10.510 align:middle line:84%
>> There's always going to be
that fear of what happens if.

00:29:10.510 --> 00:29:13.030 align:middle line:84%
What happens if
he's 20 years old

00:29:13.030 --> 00:29:15.940 align:middle line:84%
and something starts going wrong
with the sutures in his lung?

00:29:15.940 --> 00:29:19.435 align:middle line:84%
What happens if he
breaks that leg again,

00:29:19.435 --> 00:29:21.997 align:middle line:84%
and it's chronic osteomyelitis,
and it never heals, and it's

00:29:21.997 --> 00:29:23.080 align:middle line:90%
always going to be broken?

00:29:23.080 --> 00:29:24.880 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:29.723 align:middle line:84%
But I think overall I want him
to get the most out of life.

00:29:29.723 --> 00:29:30.649 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:29:30.649 --> 00:29:32.970 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:34.200 align:middle line:90%
There's something out there.

00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:38.360 align:middle line:84%
There's some reason this
kid was not allowed to go.

00:29:38.360 --> 00:29:39.920 align:middle line:84%
And I can't wait
to see what it is.

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:42.848 align:middle line:90%
[BEEPING]

00:29:42.848 --> 00:29:46.264 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:29:46.264 --> 00:29:59.389 align:middle line:90%


00:29:59.389 --> 00:30:01.430 align:middle line:84%
>> To make a difference
to antibiotic resistance,

00:30:01.430 --> 00:30:05.290 align:middle line:84%
the thing that we have to do is
to stop misusing antibiotics.

00:30:05.290 --> 00:30:08.020 align:middle line:84%
We have to stop misusing them
or using them inappropriately

00:30:08.020 --> 00:30:09.110 align:middle line:90%
in human medicine.

00:30:09.110 --> 00:30:11.110 align:middle line:84%
And we have to stop
misusing them and using them

00:30:11.110 --> 00:30:13.150 align:middle line:90%
inappropriately in agriculture.

00:30:13.150 --> 00:30:15.070 align:middle line:84%
Why do those two
things keep going on?

00:30:15.070 --> 00:30:17.540 align:middle line:84%
I think it's really two
different situations.

00:30:17.540 --> 00:30:21.070 align:middle line:84%
I think in the case of medicine,
it's mostly just inertia.

00:30:21.070 --> 00:30:24.250 align:middle line:84%
That medicine is a big,
complicated enterprise.

00:30:24.250 --> 00:30:28.150 align:middle line:84%
And it's hard to get new
best practices, I guess

00:30:28.150 --> 00:30:31.860 align:middle line:84%
they would say, into
the hands of hospitals

00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:34.400 align:middle line:84%
and to convince everyone
of what has to happen.

00:30:34.400 --> 00:30:37.550 align:middle line:84%
But in agriculture, it's
a different situation.

00:30:37.550 --> 00:30:39.730 align:middle line:84%
You hear over and over
again in agriculture,

00:30:39.730 --> 00:30:42.670 align:middle line:84%
we're not really sure if
the use of antibiotics

00:30:42.670 --> 00:30:44.020 align:middle line:90%
is contributing to resistance.

00:30:44.020 --> 00:30:46.030 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:30:46.030 --> 00:30:47.050 align:middle line:90%
Yes, it is.

00:30:47.050 --> 00:30:48.790 align:middle line:84%
It's not a scientific
question any more.

00:30:48.790 --> 00:30:50.200 align:middle line:90%
It's a question of politics.

00:30:50.200 --> 00:30:52.666 align:middle line:84%
And it's a question
of economics.

00:30:52.666 --> 00:30:54.291 align:middle line:84%
But it's really not
a science question.

00:30:54.291 --> 00:30:57.728 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:30:57.728 --> 00:31:00.674 align:middle line:90%


00:31:00.674 --> 00:31:03.802 align:middle line:90%
[CLUCKING]

00:31:03.802 --> 00:31:04.602 align:middle line:90%


00:31:04.602 --> 00:31:07.548 align:middle line:10%
[BUZZING]

00:31:07.548 --> 00:31:10.985 align:middle line:10%
[PIGS GRUNTING]

00:31:10.985 --> 00:31:13.440 align:middle line:10%


00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:18.350 align:middle line:10%
>> The agriculture believed
that with antibiotics they could

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:21.400 align:middle line:10%
grow healthier, fatter
animals quicker.

00:31:21.400 --> 00:31:23.360 align:middle line:10%
And then it evolved
the fact that they

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:25.430 align:middle line:10%
found that they could keep
animals in some pretty

00:31:25.430 --> 00:31:27.140 align:middle line:10%
