00:33:42.495 --> 00:33:46.500 align:middle line:90%


00:33:46.500 --> 00:33:51.150 align:middle line:10%
He just does that
because he can.

00:33:51.150 --> 00:33:52.480 align:middle line:90%
He knows he's not a farmer.

00:33:52.480 --> 00:33:54.925 align:middle line:90%
He's an industrial pig producer.

00:33:54.925 --> 00:33:58.340 align:middle line:90%


00:33:58.340 --> 00:34:00.890 align:middle line:84%
They're still working on that
glass building back there.

00:34:00.890 --> 00:34:04.290 align:middle line:84%
Like I said, there's a 600 head,
a 1,200 head, an 1,800 head,

00:34:04.290 --> 00:34:06.960 align:middle line:84%
and now another
1,200 head facility.

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:09.330 align:middle line:84%
But if you looked
in the building,

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:12.710 align:middle line:84%
you'll find somewhere
between 1,100 and 1,500 head

00:34:12.710 --> 00:34:17.505 align:middle line:84%
of hogs that are packed
together in tiny little pens.

00:34:17.505 --> 00:34:19.470 align:middle line:90%


00:34:19.470 --> 00:34:20.270 align:middle line:90%
They're

00:34:20.270 --> 00:34:25.060 align:middle line:84%
standing over a concrete pit
that's 8 to 12 feet deep.

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:28.110 align:middle line:84%
Antibiotics are in their
feed, in their water.

00:34:28.110 --> 00:34:31.179 align:middle line:84%
And then if there's any sign
of coughing or whatever,

00:34:31.179 --> 00:34:33.110 align:middle line:90%
they're also injected again.

00:34:33.110 --> 00:34:34.781 align:middle line:84%
And they do not
leave until they're

00:34:34.781 --> 00:34:36.530 align:middle line:84%
ready to go to the
truck and be butchered.

00:34:36.530 --> 00:34:39.482 align:middle line:90%
[WAVES CRASHING]

00:34:39.482 --> 00:34:50.330 align:middle line:90%


00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:54.050 align:middle line:84%
>> Wherever livestock are
kept, food bills always account

00:34:54.050 --> 00:34:56.540 align:middle line:84%
for a large proportion
of the cost.

00:34:56.540 --> 00:35:00.370 align:middle line:84%
A bird or animal is not
a very efficient factory

00:35:00.370 --> 00:35:03.390 align:middle line:84%
for converting animal
food into human food.

00:35:03.390 --> 00:35:06.190 align:middle line:84%
And anything that will help
to improve the efficiency

00:35:06.190 --> 00:35:09.070 align:middle line:90%
will add to the profitability.

00:35:09.070 --> 00:35:11.250 align:middle line:84%
In this, the animal
food industry

00:35:11.250 --> 00:35:13.510 align:middle line:84%
is helped by the
specialist laboratory.

00:35:13.510 --> 00:35:16.630 align:middle line:90%


00:35:16.630 --> 00:35:19.780 align:middle line:10%
>> Back 56 years ago they found
that if they gave very low

00:35:19.780 --> 00:35:22.810 align:middle line:10%
levels of antibiotics, the
animals would grow a little bit

00:35:22.810 --> 00:35:25.750 align:middle line:10%
faster than if they didn't
have the antibiotics in.

00:35:25.750 --> 00:35:26.860 align:middle line:90%
We don't know why.

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:28.090 align:middle line:90%
We didn't know why then.

00:35:28.090 --> 00:35:29.590 align:middle line:90%
We still don't know why now.

00:35:29.590 --> 00:35:31.990 align:middle line:84%
But we know that that
does make the animal's

00:35:31.990 --> 00:35:33.620 align:middle line:90%
grow a little bit faster.

00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:35.710 align:middle line:84%
So that's why it
started happening.

00:35:35.710 --> 00:35:38.530 align:middle line:84%
And we've really
grown up the industry

00:35:38.530 --> 00:35:42.010 align:middle line:84%
with putting those low levels
of antibiotics into the feed.

00:35:42.010 --> 00:35:48.420 align:middle line:10%
>> The finding was at Lederle
where the company was making

00:35:48.420 --> 00:35:51.850 align:middle line:10%
a tetracycline
for use in people.

00:35:51.850 --> 00:35:55.600 align:middle line:84%
The mash from the
tetracycline was

00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:57.880 align:middle line:84%
given to chickens
and other animals

00:35:57.880 --> 00:36:00.550 align:middle line:84%
and noted that they
seem to grow better

00:36:00.550 --> 00:36:03.510 align:middle line:90%
for the same amount of protein.

00:36:03.510 --> 00:36:06.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, it turns out that the
substance doing the growth

00:36:06.850 --> 00:36:09.730 align:middle line:84%
promotion was none
other than trace amounts

00:36:09.730 --> 00:36:12.320 align:middle line:84%
of the tetracycline
left with the carcasses.

00:36:12.320 --> 00:36:16.660 align:middle line:84%
Then the industry said, let's
just add it back to the feed.

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:19.840 align:middle line:84%
And so penicillins and
tetracyclines especially

00:36:19.840 --> 00:36:23.380 align:middle line:84%
were added back to
feed for what was then

00:36:23.380 --> 00:36:28.410 align:middle line:84%
called growth promotion,
later called feed efficiency.

00:36:28.410 --> 00:36:32.320 align:middle line:84%
And now being reexamined
because in fact

00:36:32.320 --> 00:36:34.180 align:middle line:90%
their extended use is a mistake.

00:36:34.180 --> 00:36:36.580 align:middle line:90%


00:36:36.580 --> 00:36:39.970 align:middle line:84%
>> For large corporations, what
they want to do is get as much

00:36:39.970 --> 00:36:44.420 align:middle line:84%
meat out as quickly and
as cheaply as possible.

00:36:44.420 --> 00:36:48.340 align:middle line:84%
That means putting antibiotics
in for growth promotion,

00:36:48.340 --> 00:36:50.840 align:middle line:84%
to keep the animals
from getting sick.

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:53.530 align:middle line:84%
And the whole thought
of treating the animals

00:36:53.530 --> 00:36:54.850 align:middle line:90%
gets to be almost secondary.

00:36:54.850 --> 00:36:58.510 align:middle line:90%


00:36:58.510 --> 00:37:01.080 align:middle line:84%
>> Iowa is the biggest hog
producing state in the United

00:37:01.080 --> 00:37:02.360 align:middle line:90%
States.

00:37:02.360 --> 00:37:04.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's really
interesting to look

00:37:04.490 --> 00:37:07.370 align:middle line:84%
at what happened in Iowa
over the past 25 years.

00:37:07.370 --> 00:37:12.170 align:middle line:84%
And the way that the place
that hog farming had in Iowa

00:37:12.170 --> 00:37:13.460 align:middle line:90%
changed over that period.

00:37:13.460 --> 00:37:16.170 align:middle line:84%
>> Eric [? Dee ?] produces
2,000 hogs a year on his factory

00:37:16.170 --> 00:37:16.970 align:middle line:90%
farm.

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:19.220 align:middle line:84%
He has traded in his
slop bucket for buildings

00:37:19.220 --> 00:37:22.140 align:middle line:84%
where the temperature is
controlled, the feed automated,

00:37:22.140 --> 00:37:23.720 align:middle line:90%
and the overhead expensive.

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:26.970 align:middle line:84%
In order to be profitable, this
assembly line must run nonstop.

00:37:26.970 --> 00:37:29.245 align:middle line:84%
>> We didn't find this
system of technology.

00:37:29.245 --> 00:37:31.370 align:middle line:84%
We were forced to look at
this system of technology

00:37:31.370 --> 00:37:32.840 align:middle line:90%
if we wanted to stay afloat.

00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:34.910 align:middle line:90%
[PIGS GRUNTING]

00:37:34.910 --> 00:37:41.000 align:middle line:10%
>> So between '82 and 2007, we
go from 50,000 farms to about

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:42.320 align:middle line:10%
8,000 farms.

00:37:42.320 --> 00:37:46.470 align:middle line:84%
85% of hog farms in Iowa
went out of business.

00:37:46.470 --> 00:37:51.490 align:middle line:10%
The other ones scaled
up dramatically.

00:37:51.490 --> 00:37:57.610 align:middle line:84%
The price of a hog went from
$240 in 1982 to about $109

00:37:57.610 --> 00:37:59.290 align:middle line:90%
in 2007.

00:37:59.290 --> 00:38:01.150 align:middle line:84%
So you saw the
remaining farms were

00:38:01.150 --> 00:38:03.550 align:middle line:90%
making way less profit per hog.

00:38:03.550 --> 00:38:06.160 align:middle line:10%
And that is one of the
reasons those farmers are

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:09.910 align:middle line:10%
so protective of their right
to douse their hogs every day

00:38:09.910 --> 00:38:12.790 align:middle line:10%
with antibiotics because
they've got so many of them,

00:38:12.790 --> 00:38:16.690 align:middle line:10%
they've got such tiny,
tight micro thin profit

00:38:16.690 --> 00:38:19.420 align:middle line:10%
margins that they're
under severe pressure

00:38:19.420 --> 00:38:22.420 align:middle line:10%
to produce as much as
possible, as fast as possible.

00:38:22.420 --> 00:38:24.670 align:middle line:84%
>> I'd love to be able to
say that we should only give

00:38:24.670 --> 00:38:28.410 align:middle line:84%
antibiotics when they're
absolutely, 100% necessary.

00:38:28.410 --> 00:38:30.700 align:middle line:84%
But right now in
certain industries,

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:34.834 align:middle line:84%
as the poultry industry,
the swine industry.

00:38:34.834 --> 00:38:36.750 align:middle line:90%
It's an economic necessity.

00:38:36.750 --> 00:38:40.110 align:middle line:90%


00:38:40.110 --> 00:38:42.810 align:middle line:84%
>> Confinement agriculture,
as it now exists,

00:38:42.810 --> 00:38:46.440 align:middle line:84%
could not exist without
antibiotics being used the way

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:48.100 align:middle line:90%
they are now used.

00:38:48.100 --> 00:38:50.490 align:middle line:84%
So if you took antibiotics
out of that system

00:38:50.490 --> 00:38:53.400 align:middle line:84%
or if you even dialed
back their use,

00:38:53.400 --> 00:38:55.140 align:middle line:90%
the system would have to change.

00:38:55.140 --> 00:38:58.650 align:middle line:84%
And people within that
agricultural system

00:38:58.650 --> 00:39:01.620 align:middle line:90%
say, it's not worth the cost.

00:39:01.620 --> 00:39:05.160 align:middle line:84%
Well, tell that to
a mother whose child

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:07.585 align:middle line:84%
dies of an antibiotic
resistant illness.

00:39:07.585 --> 00:39:09.210 align:middle line:84%
It's certainly worth
it to that mother.

00:39:09.210 --> 00:39:11.520 align:middle line:90%


00:39:11.520 --> 00:39:14.760 align:middle line:90%
>> April 16th, 2004--

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:18.900 align:middle line:84%
it was a Friday, absolutely
regular, normal everyday.

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:21.450 align:middle line:84%
And that morning around
6:00 in the morning,

00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:23.910 align:middle line:84%
my son who was 18
months old, my son

00:39:23.910 --> 00:39:28.050 align:middle line:84%
whose name is Simon Sparrow,
let out this shriek.

00:39:28.050 --> 00:39:30.750 align:middle line:90%
And he wasn't acting himself.

00:39:30.750 --> 00:39:32.830 align:middle line:84%
He was kind of
under the weather.

00:39:32.830 --> 00:39:35.880 align:middle line:84%
But I just thought,
oh, he's 18 months.

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:36.760 align:middle line:90%
Kids get sick.

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:37.560 align:middle line:90%
He'll be fine.

00:39:37.560 --> 00:39:42.010 align:middle line:84%
But my husband had a sense that
something was very serious.

00:39:42.010 --> 00:39:44.520 align:middle line:84%
So he said, I'm going to bring
him to the emergency room

00:39:44.520 --> 00:39:48.280 align:middle line:84%
because I really feel that
there's something wrong here.

00:39:48.280 --> 00:39:50.677 align:middle line:84%
And I actually thought
he was overreacting.

00:39:50.677 --> 00:39:51.510 align:middle line:90%
I thought, OK, yeah.

00:39:51.510 --> 00:39:52.672 align:middle line:90%
Go to the emergency room.

00:39:52.672 --> 00:39:53.880 align:middle line:90%
I'll catch up with you later.

00:39:53.880 --> 00:39:55.300 align:middle line:90%


00:39:55.300 --> 00:39:58.230 align:middle line:84%
I had to get my older
daughter ready for school.

00:39:58.230 --> 00:39:59.130 align:middle line:90%
And then I arrived.

00:39:59.130 --> 00:40:02.070 align:middle line:84%
My husband said that
the emergency room

00:40:02.070 --> 00:40:05.670 align:middle line:84%
folks had administered
all kinds of tests.

00:40:05.670 --> 00:40:08.700 align:middle line:84%
But no worries, he's
fine and can go home.

00:40:08.700 --> 00:40:10.060 align:middle line:90%


00:40:10.060 --> 00:40:13.300 align:middle line:84%
At this point, he was
increasingly having

00:40:13.300 --> 00:40:14.740 align:middle line:90%
trouble breathing.

00:40:14.740 --> 00:40:17.170 align:middle line:84%
And then right in the
middle of the afternoon

00:40:17.170 --> 00:40:19.560 align:middle line:84%
I touched his cheek
and his forehead.

00:40:19.560 --> 00:40:21.070 align:middle line:90%
And they were ice cold.

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:24.640 align:middle line:84%
And I completely freaked out
because I was used to fevers.

00:40:24.640 --> 00:40:26.920 align:middle line:84%
If you touch the
forehead and you

00:40:26.920 --> 00:40:30.280 align:middle line:84%
can tell when that child has
a fever because it's so hot.

00:40:30.280 --> 00:40:36.520 align:middle line:84%
But I had never felt ice
cold on a child's head.

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:40.180 align:middle line:84%
So I freaked out and
I called the doctor

00:40:40.180 --> 00:40:42.380 align:middle line:90%
at the emergency room.

00:40:42.380 --> 00:40:43.630 align:middle line:90%
And I explain what's going on.

00:40:43.630 --> 00:40:45.850 align:middle line:84%
And I had her actually
listened to his breathing.

00:40:45.850 --> 00:40:50.910 align:middle line:84%
And it was kind of like
[BREATHES IN AND OUT]..

00:40:50.910 --> 00:40:53.010 align:middle line:90%
And she said, hang up the phone.

00:40:53.010 --> 00:40:54.700 align:middle line:90%
Call 911 immediately.

00:40:54.700 --> 00:40:56.790 align:middle line:84%
And when the two men
from the ambulance

00:40:56.790 --> 00:41:00.330 align:middle line:84%
came up to our apartment, they
did another series of tests.

00:41:00.330 --> 00:41:01.590 align:middle line:90%
They said, he's fine.

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:03.660 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, I
felt kind of embarrassed.

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:06.040 align:middle line:90%
Like, oh my gosh, I exaggerated.

00:41:06.040 --> 00:41:08.610 align:middle line:84%
I'm making much
ado about nothing.

00:41:08.610 --> 00:41:09.410 align:middle line:90%
It's fine.

00:41:09.410 --> 00:41:10.410 align:middle line:90%
We can go home now.

00:41:10.410 --> 00:41:15.700 align:middle line:84%
But then the medical technician
said, no, because of protocol.

00:41:15.700 --> 00:41:17.814 align:middle line:84%
Once you're in the ambulance,
we have to take you

00:41:17.814 --> 00:41:18.730 align:middle line:90%
to the emergency room.

00:41:18.730 --> 00:41:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So we went to the
emergency room.

00:41:20.790 --> 00:41:24.180 align:middle line:84%
And then suddenly I had a
flood of health care people

00:41:24.180 --> 00:41:25.800 align:middle line:90%
surrounding me and Simon.

00:41:25.800 --> 00:41:28.440 align:middle line:10%
And they kept repeating your
child is very, very sick.

00:41:28.440 --> 00:41:30.300 align:middle line:90%
Your child is very, very sick.

00:41:30.300 --> 00:41:33.547 align:middle line:90%
And I was just breaking down.

00:41:33.547 --> 00:41:35.130 align:middle line:84%
And then they were
asking me questions

00:41:35.130 --> 00:41:38.110 align:middle line:84%
like has Simon been to
another country recently?

00:41:38.110 --> 00:41:38.910 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:41:38.910 --> 00:41:40.300 align:middle line:90%
Has he been to a farm recently?

00:41:40.300 --> 00:41:41.100 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:42.630 align:middle line:84%
Has he had all
his immunizations?

00:41:42.630 --> 00:41:43.695 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:41:43.695 --> 00:41:45.570 align:middle line:84%
And then they said,
well, we have to take him

00:41:45.570 --> 00:41:47.530 align:middle line:90%
to the intensive care unit.

00:41:47.530 --> 00:41:53.310 align:middle line:10%
And then, finally, when I was
allowed in, Simon was in a bed

00:41:53.310 --> 00:41:55.770 align:middle line:10%
with all kinds of
tubes connected to him.

00:41:55.770 --> 00:41:58.860 align:middle line:90%
[CHIMING]

00:41:58.860 --> 00:42:01.040 align:middle line:90%
He was intubated.

00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:03.120 align:middle line:84%
And the doctor, the
attending explained

00:42:03.120 --> 00:42:05.490 align:middle line:84%
that he's having a lot
of trouble breathing.

00:42:05.490 --> 00:42:08.610 align:middle line:84%
And she said, the only
thing that we know

00:42:08.610 --> 00:42:10.110 align:middle line:84%
is that your son
has an infection.

00:42:10.110 --> 00:42:12.670 align:middle line:84%
And he's very, very,
very, very sick.

00:42:12.670 --> 00:42:14.700 align:middle line:84%
So you need to plan to
be here for a long time.

00:42:14.700 --> 00:42:24.000 align:middle line:90%


00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:30.180 align:middle line:84%
And then they brought us into
where he was lying down in bed.

00:42:30.180 --> 00:42:33.450 align:middle line:84%
And there were at least
10 medical doctors.

00:42:33.450 --> 00:42:36.990 align:middle line:84%
And they said that the only
chance that he would have was

00:42:36.990 --> 00:42:40.740 align:middle line:84%
if they put him on this machine
called the ECMO machine,

00:42:40.740 --> 00:42:44.316 align:middle line:84%
E-C-M-O. It's a
heart-lung machine.

00:42:44.316 --> 00:42:45.690 align:middle line:84%
So, of course, we
said, OK, let's

00:42:45.690 --> 00:42:47.290 align:middle line:90%
bring him to this machine.

00:42:47.290 --> 00:42:49.260 align:middle line:84%
And it was very, very
difficult to see this

00:42:49.260 --> 00:42:53.010 align:middle line:84%
because they had to elevate him
so that the machine would work

00:42:53.010 --> 00:42:54.820 align:middle line:90%
better for gravity reasons.

00:42:54.820 --> 00:42:57.780 align:middle line:84%
And my husband stayed by
his side the whole night.

00:42:57.780 --> 00:42:59.250 align:middle line:90%
He was on a stepladder.

00:42:59.250 --> 00:43:01.670 align:middle line:84%
And he was stroking
his hair, telling him

00:43:01.670 --> 00:43:04.680 align:middle line:84%
about all the things that
they would do together

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:07.230 align:middle line:84%
like fishing, skiing,
all the things

00:43:07.230 --> 00:43:09.720 align:middle line:84%
that my husband wanted
to do with Simon.

00:43:09.720 --> 00:43:13.270 align:middle line:84%
And in the middle of night,
I was just so beside myself.

00:43:13.270 --> 00:43:16.090 align:middle line:84%
I really felt like that
Simon had already died.

00:43:16.090 --> 00:43:19.770 align:middle line:84%
And I really felt like
I needed to go back home

00:43:19.770 --> 00:43:24.100 align:middle line:84%
to where my daughter was so I
could spend some time with her.

00:43:24.100 --> 00:43:27.870 align:middle line:84%
And then I went back at
6:00, 7:00 in the morning.

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:31.950 align:middle line:84%
And that's when the doctor
said that there was really

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:35.760 align:middle line:84%
no chance that Simon
was going to make it.

00:43:35.760 --> 00:43:40.830 align:middle line:84%
And at this point,
my son was completely

00:43:40.830 --> 00:43:42.420 align:middle line:90%
transformed physically.

00:43:42.420 --> 00:43:44.520 align:middle line:90%
He was completely bloated.

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:47.350 align:middle line:84%
He had purple splotches
all over his body.

00:43:47.350 --> 00:43:50.700 align:middle line:84%
He had purple tears
coming out of his eyes.

00:43:50.700 --> 00:43:58.110 align:middle line:84%
I mean he looked totally like
a different being altogether.

00:43:58.110 --> 00:44:00.870 align:middle line:84%
And we agreed to take him
off this ECMO machine.

00:44:00.870 --> 00:44:03.770 align:middle line:84%
And that's when he
was pronounced dead.

00:44:03.770 --> 00:44:06.750 align:middle line:90%
That was April 17th, a Saturday.

00:44:06.750 --> 00:44:10.860 align:middle line:84%
And everybody was just
completely stunned.

00:44:10.860 --> 00:44:14.610 align:middle line:90%
No one knew why he had died.

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:20.880 align:middle line:84%
And we had to live with
that for about two months

00:44:20.880 --> 00:44:23.994 align:middle line:84%
when we were waiting
for the autopsy results.

00:44:23.994 --> 00:44:25.410 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we were called in.

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:28.320 align:middle line:84%
